Appraisal skill
the exclusive Appraisal skill that only the isekai protagonist possesses. This skill is unique to them alone — no other character in the world (NPCs, monsters, gods, demons, or fellow adventurers) has access to it or even knows it exists in this form. The world itself operates on a completely reality-based logic for everyone except the protagonist.
Core Mechanics of Appraisal:

What the Protagonist Sees
When the protagonist activates Appraisal (usually by focusing their gaze on a target and mentally saying or thinking “Appraise”), a transparent blue system window appears only in their vision. This window displays structured game-like information:
Name, Race, Age, Gender, Title(s)
Level (e.g., Lv. 27)
HP, MP, SP, Strength, Vitality, Agility, Magic Power, Luck (and any other stats the world uses)
Skills (with levels or ranks, e.g., Sword Mastery Lv.5, Fire Magic Lv.3, Cooking Lv.2)
Affinities, Resistances, Blessings/Curses
Condition (Poisoned, Fatigued, etc.)
Potential / Hidden Talents (sometimes visible only at higher Appraisal levels)
For items: Rarity, Effects, Durability, Hidden Properties, Required Stats to use, Crafting Requirements, Value in gold.
Information level is base on the level of the Appraisal skill

Activation & Cost
Costs a small amount of MP or mental stamina per use.
Can be used on people, monsters, animals, plants, items, buildings, traps, or even the air/magic in the environment.
At higher proficiency, Appraisal can be used silently, at range, or in rapid succession without the protagonist visibly staring.

Reality vs. Game Layer
Crucially: The world does NOT run on game mechanics for its inhabitants.
NPCs and monsters live fully realistic lives. A farmer does not think in “levels” or “skill points.” He simply gets better at farming through years of practice and experience.
A knight does not see his own “Sword Mastery Lv.7.” He only feels that he has trained hard and become quite skilled with the blade.
Magic exists and follows its own natural laws (mana, chants, affinities), but people do not see MP bars or spell cooldowns.
Monsters get stronger with age and feeding, not by gaining “XP.”
Death, aging, pregnancy, emotions, economies, politics — everything functions with real-world logic and consequences.
The protagonist is the only person who perceives this hidden “game layer” overlay. This creates constant dramatic irony and strategic advantage.
Progression of Appraisal
The skill itself can level up through use:
Initial Appraisal: Basic stats and visible skills.
Intermediate: Hidden skills, exact numerical values, weaknesses.
Advanced: Future growth predictions, loyalty/affection meters, detailed item creation recipes, true names of legendary beings, even glimpses of “fate” or hidden quests.
Ultimate: Possibly reading thoughts, seeing through illusions perfectly, or appraising abstract concepts (a country’s military strength, a person’s trauma, the quality of a relationship).

Skill levels seen by appraisal
When the protagonist uses Appraisal, every skill is displayed with a clear rank from G to SSS. These ranks represent the absolute level of mastery and power of that skill in the world, visible only to the protagonist. No other character in the world knows or thinks in these letter grades — they only feel “I’m pretty good at this” or “I’ve trained for decades.”
Skill Rank Scale & Descriptions

G Rank – Complete Beginner / Novice
Barely functional. The person has only just learned the skill or is using it for the first time. Extremely weak, full of mistakes, low efficiency.
Example: A farmer who just picked up a sword for the first time (Sword Mastery G).
F Rank – Beginner / Amateur
Basic understanding. Can use the skill in simple situations but struggles with anything complex. Common among average villagers and new adventurers.
Example: A village girl who helps in the kitchen sometimes (Cooking F).
E Rank – Lower Intermediate
Reliable for everyday use. Noticeable improvement, but still far from professional. Most working adults in their field sit around here.
D Rank – Upper Intermediate
Solid and dependable. Can handle normal jobs and light combat/adventure work without issue. This is the level of a well-trained soldier or experienced craftsman.
C Rank – Advanced / Expert
Clearly above average. Recognized as talented in their town or guild. High success rate, can teach beginners, and performs well under pressure.
This is where most competent adventurers or skilled tradespeople plateau.
B Rank – Master Practitioner
Exceptional skill. Renowned in a city or small region. Can do things most people consider impossible for their profession. Very high efficiency and creativity with the skill.
Example: A famous local blacksmith known for high-quality weapons (Blacksmithing B).
A Rank – True Master / Peak Human Mastery
This is the benchmark for “master of the profession.”
A person at A rank is considered one of the best in their entire country or field. Their technique is nearly flawless, they can innovate, and their results are on another level. Kings and top guilds actively seek them out.
Example: A legendary swordsman who has trained for 30+ years, or the royal court’s head magician.
A-rank is where the protagonist usually starts treating someone as genuinely formidable.
S Rank – Legendary / Superhuman
Transcends normal human limits. One or two such people exist per country at most. Their skill borders on the realm of myth. They can casually do things that would be considered miracles by normal standards.
Example: A hero from legends, an ancient dragon’s Breath Attack, or the founder of a sword style.
SS Rank – Mythical / World-Class Monster
Extremely rare. Maybe only a handful exist on the entire continent. Their power and mastery warp common sense. Even nations tremble at the mention of their name.
Example: Ancient Demon Lords, Dragon Kings, or the greatest sages in history.
SSS Rank – God-Tier / Reality-Bending
Almost never seen. The absolute pinnacle. Skills at this level can affect the laws of the world itself. Only heroes summoned from another world, ancient gods, or final-boss-level beings usually possess them.
Example: A skill that can cut through dimensions, resurrect the dead, or rewrite magic itself.

Key Differences & Flavor Rules

Each rank up represents a massive qualitative leap, not just +10% power.
Going from B to A is like going from “very talented” to “once-in-a-generation genius.”
Going from A to S feels like stepping into the realm of legends.
Skill Synergy: When Appraisal shows multiple high-rank skills on one person, the protagonist immediately knows they are facing a monster (e.g., Sword Mastery A + Magic Power SS = terrifying threat).
Growth Visibility: The protagonist can also see when the skill is advancing, and how close they are to ranking up by (+) plus indicators

Limitations & Flavor
Cannot directly change reality — it only reveals information.
Very powerful or ancient entities may have partial resistance (the window shows “Appraisal Blocked” or distorted data).
Overuse can cause headaches, eye strain, or temporary blindness in the protagonist.
The system window is invisible and inaudible to everyone else. The protagonist must verbally explain (or lie about) what he sees.
Creates delicious tension: the protagonist knows exactly how strong someone is, what skills they’re hiding, or how valuable an item truly is, while the rest of the world remains ignorant.


This Appraisal skill turns the protagonist into the only person who sees the world as a litRPG/game system, while everyone around him lives in a grounded fantasy reality. Use this for deep strategic thinking, power-level checks, item identification, social manipulation, and constant “only I know” moments. Always maintain the separation between the protagonist’s meta-vision and the living, breathing world the other characters experience.

